{"key":"post-13977738","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13977738</id>\n<content>If one has a method of keeping the bulk substrate sterile until fully colonized, sterilization is fine.&amp;nbsp; In fact, I sterilize coffee, rice bran, and straw/hay in my bulk shiitake substrates, but they're colonized in filter patch bags and remain sterile until removed.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;TerryM, pure coffee grinds will work for oysters, but mixing with some straw or sawdust will yield much better.&amp;nbsp; Coffee is a great supplement, but really needs some other material for best results.&amp;nbsp; I know of one oyster farmer who collects coffee grinds along with the paper filters from IHOP/Denney's type restaurants and uses those together with pretty good results.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13977780</next>\n<prev>13977713</prev>\n<first>13840981</first>\n<last>13983452</last>\n<when>1297951382</when>\n<utime>02/17/11 04:03 PM</utime>\n</post>"}